movie_description: From 1965 through 1975, the groundbreaking British sitcom Till Death Us Do Part was shown on BBC1 in the United Kingdom. After making its debut as a pilot episode on Comedy Playhouse, the show ran for a total of seven seasons until 1975. Six years later, ITV picked up where it left off with the sitcom and gave it the name Till Death.... A sequel titled "In Sickness and in Health" was produced by the BBC from 1985 to 1992. Till Death Us Do Part was written by Johnny Speight and centered on the East End Garnett family. The show's father, Alf Garnett, is a reactionary white working-class man who harbors racist and anti-socialist ideas. Johnny Speight was the show's creator. Dandy Nichols was the actress who played his patient and kind wife Else, while Una Stubbs was the one who portrayed their daughter Rita. Mike Rawlins, Rita's intelligent but somewhat slacker of a husband, is a communist. Mitchell portrayed the role of Alf Garnett on stage and television up until 1998, when Speight passed away. Over the course of his career, Alf Garnett became a well-known figure in the culture of the United Kingdom. In addition to the spin-off film In Sickness and in Health, the original film Till Death Us Do Part has been remade in a number of countries, including the United States of America, Germany, and Brazil. It is believed that a good number of episodes from the first three series no longer exist since they were destroyed in the late 1960s and early 1970s in accordance with the protocol that was in place at the time.
cast: Dandy Nichols, Una Stubbs, Tony Booth, Warren Mitchell,

movie_description: The eponymous spaceship of the Space Battleship Yamato appears in the Japanese science fiction anime series Space Battleship Yamato. This version's first two seasons were aired in Greece under the moniker "A" during the 1981–1982 television season. A Portuguese-language version was successfully shown in Brazil under the title Patrulha Estelar and in Spain and Latin America it was known as either Viaje a la Ultima Galaxia or Astronave Intrepido. An Italian-language adaptation of the show was also broadcast in Italy and went by the name Star Blazers in that country. It is a seminal series in the history of anime, marking a turn towards more complex serious works and influencing works such as Mobile Suit Gundam and Neon Genesis Evangelion; Hideaki Anno has ranked Yamato as his favorite anime, and he credits it with sparking his interest in anime. Yamato is a seminal series in the history of anime. The Seiun Award was not given out again for an anime series or movie again until 1985 for Nausicaa of the Valley of the Wind. movie_description: Sherwood Schwartz is responsible for the creation of the American sitcom Gilligan's Island, which was originally produced by United Artists Television. Schwartz also serves as the show's executive producer. Bob Denver, Alan Hale Jr., Jim Backus, Natalie Schafer, Tina Louise, and Russell Johnson were among the cast members of the situation comedy series. Dawn Wells also appeared on the show. Beginning on September 26, 1964 and running through September 4, 1967, it was broadcast on the CBS network for a total of three seasons. The show initially featured the comedic exploits of seven castaways as they fought to live on the island on which they had been stranded. Philip Morris & Company and Procter & Gamble were the companies that sponsored the show when it first aired. The tensions between the many castaways and their unsuccessful attempts to escape their predicament are the primary focus of the majority of the show's episodes. There were a total of 98 episodes produced for the television series Gilligan's Island. The first season of the show was produced in black-and-white and consisted of a total of 36 episodes. After then, these programs received a color makeover for syndication. Color photography was utilized for the production of the show's second and third seasons, as well as all three television movie sequels. The show was successful in the ratings during its initial run, and it continued to grow in popularity during the decades that it was broadcast in syndication, particularly in the 1970s and 1980s when many markets broadcasted it in the late afternoon or evening after school had let out. Today, the titular character of the television show Gilligan is widely acknowledged as an important figure in American popular culture.

movie_description: Family Feud is an American game show where two families compete against each other to name the most popular answers to a survey question asked of 100 people. Mark Goodson and Bill Todman made the show in the United States, and it now airs in a lot of different formats around the world. Family Feud has been on TV for 30 different seasons since its first season in 1976. The show started on ABC in 1976, and Richard Dawson hosted it until it ended in 1985. By that time, it was popular both on the network and in syndication. The show was brought back by CBS in 1988, and Ray Combs was the host. In 1992, it became an hour-long show, and it ended in 1993. Combs also hosted the show's related syndicated series until 1994, when Dawson took over for one season. During that time, the show went from 30 minutes to an hour and was cancelled in 1995. movie_description: There were three seasons of VR Troopers produced by Saban Entertainment between 1994 and 1996. The show aimed to capitalize on the early 1990s infatuation with virtual reality and the success of Power Rangers. The show included early CGI and video effects blended with Japanese stock material from three separate Metal Hero series: Superhuman Machine Metalder, Dimensional Warrior Spielban, and Space Sheriff Shaider. This tokusatsu adaptation was one of the first to adopt an adaptation approach like this, which combines numerous shows into a single one, and it was initially used in anime series like Robotech and Voltron. The copyright for VR Troopers was transferred to SCG Power Rangers on May7, 2010. Saban's VR Troopers was the first "sister show" to the most popular "action fighting kid show" at the time, Mighty Morphin' Power Rangers. In a similar vein, Toei Company LTD. adapted a Japanese tokusatsu children's show for the US market.. The series was deemed popular, though not as successful as the Power Ranger franchise. Unfortunately for the series, the Japanese footage was quickly exhausted due to extreme circumstances where many tokusatsu scenarios were combined in one episode to the extent that stock video had to be reused several times throughout the series. A similar situation occurred with another Saban cartoon called Big Bad Beetleborgs, which was a hit but ended quickly owing to a lack of footage. Both of these shows are based on the original Metal Heroes manga and anime from Japan. Because of the series' success, toy and video game manufacturers followed suit.
cast: Mike Reynolds, Michael Sorich, Kerrigan Mahan, Wendee Lee, Sarah Brown

Historical luminaries like Helen Keller and Mark Twain, as well as long-dead entertainers like Will Rogers and John Barrymore, were featured in the previous version. Marilyn Monroe, Elvis Presley, Plácido Domingo, Freddie Mercury, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, Eric Clapton, Pope John Paul II, Gene Tierney, Selena, Diego Rivera, Mao Zedong, and Queen Elizabeth II, as well as fictional characters such as The Phantom, Superman, Hamlet, Betty Boop, and Santa Claus, have all been featured in the A&E series. The program profiled enough people that A&E split it off into its own network, The Biography Channel, in 1999. The majority of the episodes initially focused on the lives of historical figures or current political or social leaders. William Shakespeare, Charles Dickens, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Enrico Caruso, and Eva Peron were among the people highlighted. However, after a few years, the show began producing episodes about celebrities such as Britney Spears, Al Pacino, Johnny Depp, and Marilyn Manson. Some have questioned this shift away from exclusively academic subjects.

It also makes many references to other versions of the franchise, including many cases and creatures from the first Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!. movie_description: At the Movies is a TV show made by Disney-ABC Domestic Television in which two film critics talk about new movies. The program was shown under different names. Its first hosts were Roger Ebert of the Chicago Sun-Times and WLS-TV and Gene Siskel of the Chicago Tribune and WBBM-TV. Richard Roeper of the Sun-Times became Ebert's regular partner in 2000, after Siskel's death in 1999. In 2006, Ebert stopped making appearances so he could get treatment for thyroid cancer. Various guest hosts filled in for him. From April to August of 2008, Michael Phillips of the Chicago Tribune cohosted. On September 6, 2008, film critic and reporter for E! Entertainment Television Ben Lyons and Sirius Satellite Radio host, former co-host of The Young Turks, and current Turner Classic Movies host Ben Mankiewicz took over as hosts. On August 5, 2009, it was announced that Michael Phillips and A. O. Scott, a film critic for the New York Times, would return to the show on September 5, 2009. During its run with Siskel and Ebert as hosts, the series was nominated seven times for Primetime Emmy Awards and once for Outstanding Information Series. The last nomination was in 1997. It was well-known for the "thumbs up/thumbs down" reviews given by Siskel and Ebert. The show was shown in syndication in the United States and on CTV in Canada. It was also shown throughout the week on the cable network ReelzChannel.

movie_description: The Life and Times of Tim is a comedy animated television series that debuted on HBO on September28,2008, and has been airing ever since. There were rumblings that it would be broadcast on another network, which fueled the speculation. It was revealed on the 16th of August,2010, that HBO had changed their mind about canceling the show, and as a direct result, a third season has been given the green light to be produced. The premiere of The Life and Times of Tim season 3 took place on December 16th, 2011. On February9,2010, the first season of the show was made available on DVD. On December13,2011, the second season was made available on DVD, and on December18,2012, the third season was made available on DVD. After three seasons, HBO decided to discontinue the show on April20,2012, therefore ending the series. Each judge is given a category to which they are assigned and acts as a mentor to the contestants competing in that category. movie_description: The South Korean historical drama Ja Myung Go came out in 2009. It stars Jung Ryeo-won, Park Min-young, and Jung Kyung-ho. It is based on the Korean folk tale Prince Hodong and the Princess of Nakrang, which tells about the Nakrang Kingdom and how it fell apart. According to the story, there was a famous drum called the jamyeonggo, which means "the drum that beats by itself." This mysterious drum had the power to automatically sound an alarm whenever enemies attacked its kingdom. But the prince fell in love with the princess of Nakrang, which was a surprise. For her love, the princess decided to betray her country by tearing off the drum. Because of this, her country fell apart, and she was killed. Prince Hodong held her body and cried over her death. The drama series, on the other hand, adds a new twist by making the drum a person. Ja-myung, the Nakrang Kingdom princess's hidden sister, plays the role of the drum. Ra-hee grows up as the princess of Nakrang, where everyone loves her. Ja-myung, on the other hand, survives an attempt on her life and lives as a commoner. Prince Hodong is from the Goguryeo Kingdom, which is at war with Nakrang. He is torn between two countries and two women, and he must choose between love and duty.

movie_description: The CIA was the focus of the CBS drama series The Agency. Michael Frost Beckner was the show's creator and executive producer, along with Shaun Cassidy Productions and Radiant Productions, which worked with Universal Network Television and CBS Productions to bring the show to the screen. It ran for two seasons, from September 27, 2001 through May 17, 2003. This was the first time footage from the actual CIA headquarters had been used in a film. The show's treatment of the ethical dilemmas that arise in intelligence work and its examination of current international issues were both contentious. After Osama Bin Laden's Al Qaeda terrorist network plans a lethal strike on the West, Beckner wrote a pilot script for a re-invented CIA tasked with the "War on Terror." It was scheduled to premiere on September 18, 2001, however the 9/11 events caused CBS to postpone the premiere and air a later episode instead of holding the pilot. The first episode of the first season was rerun as episode number three. When the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks occurred, "The Agency" was one of the most topical offerings on network television at the time. This transformed how Americans saw current entertainment. This new American perspective on global issues was enthusiastically embraced by the series' creators, but CBS decided to cancel the show shortly after the conclusion of the second season.

movie_description: The Tripods is a television version of John Christopher's novel series of the same name. It was co-produced by the BBC in the UK and the Seven Network in Australia. The first series of The Tripods, which aired in 1984 and featured 13 half-hour episodes written by Alick Rowe, a well-known creator of many radio plays, covers the first book, The White Mountains; the 12-episode second series covers The City of Gold and Lead. Although a television script for the third series had been completed, it was never produced. The first series was available on VHS and DVD. In March 2009, the BBC published Tripods - The Complete Series 1 & 2 on DVD. The TV series introduced several minor changes from the book, most notably the shape of the Masters and Tripods, which in the book have tentacles; gravity inside the Golden City was artificially increased, which is not mentioned in the TV series; the introduction of "cognoscs," spiritual life-forms vastly superior to the Masters themselves; and more other main characters, including love interests for both Will and Beanpole. Female characters are scarce in the original texts. In an interview with Wordcandy, John Christopher was asked about this, and he responded that at the time of creating the series, it was usually recognized that girls would read books with boy main characters, but not vice versa. He also remarked that the addition of a full family of daughters to the TV show was "over the top." The series is particularly remarkable for its inclusion of non-humanoid aliens, which was unusual at the time.

movie_description: From 1971 through 1982, the ZDF television network in Germany broadcast a program titled "Disco," which included popular music. In most cases, it was shown on the first Saturday of the month at 7:30 PM, and each presentation lasted for a total of forty-five minutes. There were 133 different shows that were made. Ilja Richter, a German actor and comedian, served as the host of the show. Its predecessor, which was not as well known, was called 4-3-2-1 Hot & Sweet and it was shown on ZDF between the years 1966 and 1970. Some of the presenters on that show included Ilja Richter and Suzanne Doucet. In comparison to ZDF's Hitparade, which catered to an older, more rock-oriented audience, Disco often catered to a younger audience that was more pop-oriented. Up until 1972, its primary opponent was ARD's Beat-Club, followed by Musikladen. After the channel's cancellation on 3sat in 1989, ZDF Musikkanal began airing repeats of Disco in 1984 and has continued to do so up until the present day. Since 2004, the ZDF Theaterkanal, which is broadcast digitally, has been airing repeated episodes of the complete series. Reruns of the series first aired in 2007 on ZDF Dokukanal, beginning with episodes from the year 1975. In 2008, hit24 began airing repeated replays of the series as well. The program mostly focused on chart songs that were recent at the time it was broadcast, devoting roughly the same amount of attention to international pop music as it did to German Schlager. Despite the fact that it was called "Disco Music," it did not concentrate primarily on that genre of music; however, it did play a lot of disco singles as long as they were still chart-relevant.

movie_description: The Andy Griffith Show is an American sitcom that debuted on CBS on October3,1960, and ran until April1, 1968. Andy Griffith portrays the widower sheriff of the made-up North Carolina town of Mayberry. His life is hampered by an incompetent, but well-intentioned deputy named Barney Fife, a spinster aunt and housekeeper named Aunt Bee, and a brilliant little son named Opie. His life is further complicated by local scoundrels, inept companions, and temperamental girlfriends. Regarding the era of the show, Andy Griffith noted in an interview with Today: "Well, even though we never said it and even though it was filmed in the 1960s, it had a '30s vibe. We were reminiscent of a bygone era at the moment." The sitcom never finished lower than seventh in the Nielsen ratings and finished its last season at the top spot. According to TV Guide, it is the ninth-best television program in American history. movie_description: The X Factor is a British television singing competition in which aspirant singers picked from public auditions compete to discover fresh singing talent. Simon Cowell's show premiered in September 2004 and has since aired annually from August/September through December. This program is produced by FremantleMedia's Thames and Simon Cowell's SYCOtv production firm. It is televised on ITV in the United Kingdom and TV3 in Ireland, with a spin-off behind-the-scenes program called The Xtra Factor airing on ITV2. It is the creator of The X Factor franchise on a global scale. The X Factor was created as a successor for the extremely successful Pop Idol, which was put on indefinite hiatus following its second season. Cowell, who served as a judge on Pop Idol, wanted to begin a show for which he controlled the broadcast rights. Later, a legal battle arose over the perceived similarities between the two television programs. The "X Factor" in the title refers to the indefinable "something" that makes a star. Cowell, Sharon Osbourne, and Louis Walsh were the original judges. In series four, Dannii Minogue joined the panel, and after Osbourne's departure in series five, Cheryl Cole took her place. After the seventh season, both Simon Cowell and Cheryl Cole left to judge the American version of the program, while Kylie Minogue left due to her commitments on Australia's Got Talent. Kelly Rowland, Tulisa Contostavlos, and Gary Barlow then joined Walsh on the judging panel for the eighth season, although Rowland declared she would not be returning for the ninth season, and was replaced by Nicole Scherzinger. In 2013, Osbourne succeeded Contostavlos upon his return. Dermot O'Leary, who replaced Kate Thornton as the show's host in 2007, has hosted the program since 2007. Following the candidates from auditions until the grand finale, the program is divided into a series of phases. During the show's initial televised audition process, candidates sang in an audition room in front of only the judges. Beginning with the sixth season, contestants perform in front of the judges and a live audience on stage. Successful auditionees advance to "bootcamp" and then to "judges' houses," where judges filter down the acts in their category to three or four artists to mentor for the live shows, during which the audience votes for their favorite acts based on weekly live performances by the competitors.

movie_description: NBC airs its news and interview program, Meet the Press, on a weekly basis in the United States of America. Despite bearing little relation to the original format of the program that was seen in its television debut on November6,1947, it is the longest-running television series in the history of American broadcasting and holds the record for being the longest-running television series overall. Among the various Sunday morning talk shows broadcast on American television, the one with the highest ratings is "Meet the Press." It was first presented by Martha Rountree, who was followed by 10 other moderators. David Gregory is the current host of the show; he has held this position since December of 2008. On May 2, 2010, the show started using a new set, which featured video screens and a library-style set with bookshelves, as well as different and modified intro music, with David Gregory previewing the guests using a large video screen, and with the Meet the Press theme music in a shorter "modernized [style]... the beginning repeated with drum beats." The show debuted with these changes. Interviews with national leaders on problems of politics, economics, foreign policy, and other public concerns are the focus of the television program Meet the Press and other programs with a similar format. The program's typical time slot on the NBC network has been between 9 and 10 a.m. local time in most markets for the past few years. However, the exact time may change from market to market due to commitments that affiliates have made to other programming, such as religious programming, E/I programming, or local news and public affairs programming. The morning coverage of the French Open tennis tournament or the Monaco Grand Prix by NBC Sports also causes it to fluctuate for several weeks during the summer. The program used to be broadcast on Sundays at noon back in the earlier years. A replay of the program may also be seen on MSNBC on Sunday afternoons at 2 p.m. ET and early Monday mornings at 4 a.m. ET. Additionally, NBC's "All Night" programming features a repeat of the program at 4 a.m. ET on early Mondays. The program is also broadcast as a part of C-SPAN Radio's rebroadcast of the Sunday morning talk shows. It is syndicated by Dial Global and made available to radio stations around the country.
cast: Tim Russert,

movie_description: POV is a public television series on the Public Broadcasting Service that features independent nonfiction films. Point of view is abbreviated as POV. The films of POV have a strong first-person, social-issue concentration. The POV series has featured the work of a number of renowned directors, including Michael Moore, Jonathan Demme, Terry Zwigoff, Errol Morris, Albert and David Maysles, Michael Apted, Frederick Wiseman, Marlon Riggs, and Ross McElwee. Throughout its twenty-plus years on television, the series has earned both critical and industry praise. POV programs have also won prestigious industry accolades, including three Oscars, thirty-two Emmys, thirty-six Cine Golden Eagles, fifteen Peabody Awards, eleven Alfred I. duPont-Columbia Awards, the Prix Italia, and the Webby Award.

movie_description: Sunrise Studios' The Vision of Escaflowne is a 26-episode Japanese anime television series directed by Kazuki Akane. The series was also broadcast on Sony's anime satellite channel, Animax, in Japan and on its international networks, including Hong Kong, Taiwan, Southeast Asia, and South Asia. Bandai Entertainment has licensed the series for release in Region 1. When a lad named Van emerges on the high school track while facing a dragon, Hitomi, a teenage high school student, is taken from Earth to the planet Gaea. She gets trapped in the thick of a conflict in Gaea, as the Zaibach Empire tries to take over the country. Van leads his mystical mech Escaflowne in the fight against the Zaibach Empire, with Allen's assistance. In Gaea, Hitomi's fortune-telling abilities bloom as she becomes the key to reawakening Escaflowne and foiling Zaibach's schemes. During the development of the anime series, two manga retellings of the narrative were created and released: a shnen version of the story called The Vision of Escaflowne and a shjo version called Hitomi—The Vision of Escaflowne. In1997, Escaflowne—Memories, Energist's a second shjo adaptation, was published in a single book. Yumiko Tsukamoto, Hajime Yatate, and Shoji Kawamori adapted the narrative into a six-book light novel series. Escaflowne: The Movie, a film adaptation, was released on June24,2000, but it has little similarity to the original series. In addition, the series has four CD soundtracks and a drama CD.

movie_description: Those Who Kill is a Danish crime TV series that debuted in 2011 and follows a fictitious squad inside the Copenhagen Police Department that is dedicated to investigating cases of serial murder. In Denmark, each episode of the series was split into two parts, but in most other countries, each episode was longer than a feature film. Denmark was the only country to screen the series in its original format. A standalone feature film with a running time of 92 minutes called Fortidens skygge, which serves as both a continuation and conclusion to the series, had its world premiere in Danish theaters on March 15, 2012. The film is currently being broadcast as the series' sixth and final episode in many other countries, including the United Kingdom and Germany. Elsbeth Egholm and Stefan Jaworski are responsible for the creation of the series as well as the writing of each episode. A number of other screenwriters, such as Siv Rajendram, Rikke De Fine Licht, and Morten Dragsted, contributed to the production of the series by writing individual episodes. Directors have been Birger Larsen, Niels Nørløv and Kasper Barfoed. Co-production companies from Denmark, Germany, Sweden, and Norway worked together to create this series. As a result of declining audience shares after the first few episodes, Danish TV2 decided in October 2011 that there would be no further seasons made of the show, despite the fact that it had been planned to run for several seasons initially and that it was scheduled to run for several seasons. The manager of programming for TV2, Keld Reinicke, remarked that "We have no intentions to continue the series because it never brought us the audience share that we expected in Denmark."

movie_description: Lassie is a popular television show from the United States that chronicles the exploits of a female Rough Collie dog named Lassie and her traveling friends, both human and otherwise. Television broadcasts of the show began on September 12, 1954, and continued until March 24, 1973. The show was conceived of by producer Robert Maxwell and animal trainer Rudd Weatherwax. The show, which is now considered one of the longest-running on television, originally aired on CBS for a total of seventeen seasons before going into first-run syndication for its final two seasons. The show was initially filmed in black and white, but in 1965, it made the switch to color filming. The first 10 seasons of this television series chronicle Lassie's exploits in a bucolic farming village. Lassie's first human companions are a fictional eleven-year-old boy named Jeff Miller, his mother, and his grandfather. This continues until the fourth season, when Lassie is joined by a seven-year-old boy named Timmy Martin and his adoptive parents. In the eleventh season, as Lassie's antics on the farm come to an end, she joins a series of Rangers from the United States Forest Service and goes on new adventures in the forest with them. Lassie eventually finds a new home at a children's home for her final two seasons of syndication after spending the previous year wandering the country without human leads. The first season of Lassie won two Emmy Awards and earned positive reviews from critics when it originally aired. Emmy nominations have been submitted for stars Jan Clayton and June Lockhart. During the life of the show, a variety of other products such as books, a Halloween costume, apparel, and toys were made as merchandise. The show's longtime sponsor, Campbell's Soup, provided two premiums, of which thousands were given out to the show's loyal followers. In August of 1963, the feature picture Lassie's Great Adventure was released, and it contained an episode that was broken up into multiple parts. Jon Provost, who had previously starred in the television series Lassie, made his return to the medium in the role of Steve McCullough in the 1989 season of The New Lassie. A selection of the episodes has been made available on DVD.
cast: June Lockhart, Jon Provost, Hugh Reilly, George Cleveland, Josh Albee

People were enticed to meet with a decoy under the guise of sexual intercourse, only to be confronted afterwards. "People who are interested in prepubescent sex are pedophiles," he explained. In November 2004, the series premiered, with a total of 12 investigations taking place around the United States. With the support of online watchdog group Perverted-Justice, the investigations were performed as undercover sting operations. Law enforcement and other officials have been involved since the third installment, resulting in the arrests of the majority of those captured. Since December of 2007, no new episodes have broadcast. To Catch a Predator has been aired locally on the NBC stations WTMJ in Milwaukee, KSHB in Kansas City, and WBRE. To Catch a Con Man, To Catch an ID Thief, To Catch a Car Thief, and To Catch an i-Jacker, all of which featured iPod thieves, were among the many spin-offs that aired in the same format. To Catch a Predator is also broadcast in the United Kingdom on FX and the Crime & Investigation Network, as well as in Australia and New Zealand on the Crime & Investigation Network and in Portugal on FOX Crime.

movie_description: Arena was a competitive gaming television show on G4/G4techTV that ran from 2002 to 2004. The format of the show was a LAN party where teams competed in multiplayer video games. Wil Wheaton and Travis Oates were the show's initial hosts, but both quit owing to issues with the show's producer, Jim Downs, many of which Wheaton revealed in a Slashdot post. Lee Reherman and Michael Louden have taken their place. Reherman and Kevin Pereira were the last hosts. Studio 2 was used to film the first two seasons. Filming moved to Studio3, the largest studio in G4's old headquarters, in 2004 for the show's third and final season. It is broadcast occasionally on the Popgirl show. In the final episode of the series, "Bye Bye Nikki? Part2," an acoustic version of the theme song originally performed by Brian Melo was featured. The final season of Sixteen consisted of a total of 93 episodes. Both the United States of America and Canada have contributed to the production of DVDs and iTunes releases. Despite the fact that the show has been cancelled, creators Pertsch and McGillis have shown their openness to working on a reunion film or telemovie of up to two hours in length. The show is not presently scheduled to air on Cartoon Network at this time; however, episodes are still available to view on Cartoon Network on Demand in certain regions. On January3,2011, 6teen began airing repeats on Teletoon. The show currently airs on Saturday mornings at 3:00 a.m. Eastern Standard Time (EST), and it has only just begun airing on weekdays at 7:00 p.m. EST, which was its original time slot. movie_description: Matador is a Danish television series that was produced and shown from 1978 to 1982. Between 1929 and 1947, the story takes place in the fictitious Danish village of Korsbaek. It focuses on the competition between the families of two businessmen: the banker Hans Christian Varns, an established local aristocrat, and the social climber Mads Skjern, who comes in town at the beginning of the series. The series' tentative English title, Matador, was derived from a localized version of the board game Monopoly. In addition, the term "matador" is frequently used to denote a business magnate in modern Danish; in the series, it refers to the character Mads Skjern and his entrepreneurial cunning. Matador was conceived by novelist Lise Nrgaard, who co-wrote the majority of the episodes with Karen Smith, Jens Louis Petersen, and Paul Hammerich. The series was directed by renowned Danish filmmaker Erik Balling. The series is one of the most well-known and well-liked examples of Danish television and represents the culmination of the long-term development of Danish television drama by the public service channel Danmarks Radio. The series has become a part of the modern self-understanding of Danes, partly due to its successful blend of melodrama and a distinct warm Danish humour in the depiction of characters, which were portrayed by a wide range of the most popular Danish actors of the time; but also not least because of its accurate depiction of a turbulent Denmark from around the beginning of the Great Depression and through Nazi Germany's occupation of Denmark during World War II.

movie_description: Leave It to Beaver is an American situation comedy about a curious and often naive boy named Theodore "The Beaver" Cleaver and his adventures at home, in school, and around his suburban neighborhood. Beaver's parents, June and Ward Cleaver, were played by Barbara Billingsley and Hugh Beaumont, and Beaver's brother, Wally, was played by Tony Dow. In the US, the show has become an icon, and the Cleavers have come to represent the idealized suburban family of the middle of the 20th century. Writers Joe Connelly and Bob Mosher came up with the idea for the show. The lives, experiences, and conversations of their own children gave these radio and early TV veterans ideas for the show's characters, plots, and dialogue. Leave It to Beaver was one of the first sitcoms to be written from the point of view of a child. Leave It to Beaver, like many other shows from the late 1950s and early 1960s, shows what it was like to grow up as a white middle-class boy in America. In a typical episode, Beaver would get into some kind of trouble, and then his parents would tell him off and tell him what to do instead. But neither parent knew everything. In fact, the show often showed the parents arguing about how to raise their kids, and some episodes were based on mistakes made by the parents.

movie_description: Bottom is a British anarchic sitcom that was written by the comedy duo Rik Mayall and Adrian Edmondson, who also starred in the show. The show follows the lives of two social outcasts who are trapped together in a daily grind in a squalid flat in Hammersmith, London. Richie Richard is socially awkward and sexually inexperienced, and Eddie Hitler is a carefree alcoholic. They have no money, nothing to do, and are sexually dissatisfied, so they spend their days plotting, fighting, and being mean and cruel to one another. They are always poor. Following the completion of the show's initial three series, which were broadcast on BBC Two between the years 1991 and 1995, there were a total of five stage show tours presented all across the United Kingdom between the years 1993 and 2003, as well as a feature film titled Guest House Paradiso. The program is famous for its violent comic slapstick as well as its anarchic and nihilistic sense of humor. In 2008, a poll conducted by the BBC to identify "Britain's Best Sitcom" placed Bottom at position number 45 overall. The program is still broadcast in the United Kingdom on the channels Gold and Dave, and it has also been localized into a number of other languages through dubbing. In Spain, the program is referred to as "La pareja basura," and it was broadcast on Canal+. The Bum Notes, a band in whom Edmondson was a member at one point, were the ones responsible for providing the theme song, which is a cover of "Last Night" by The Mar-Keys. In 2012, preparations were made for a spin-off series to be shown on the BBC under the name Hooligan's Island. This series would star Richie and Eddie from Bottom. movie_description: Felicia Day, who also stars in the show as Cyd Sherman, is the show's creator as well as its writer. The Guild is an American comedic web series. On July 27, 2007, it was uploaded to YouTube for the first time. The first episodes of seasons two through five of the web series were made available on Xbox Live Marketplace, Zune Marketplace, and MSN Video by Microsoft. After some time, the webisodes were published on the official Guild website, as well as on YouTube and iTunes. According to Day, Microsoft's revenue model shifted after the fifth season; as Day wanted to maintain ownership, he relocated the episode premieres to his channel on YouTube, Geek & Sundry. The webisodes can also be viewed online via streaming services such as Hulu and Netflix, as well as on DVD. The show follows the members of an online gaming guild known as The Knights of Good as they spend countless hours participating in a fantasy massively multiplayer online role-playing game known simply as The Game. The main character of the story is Codex, the Priestess of the guild, who tries to carry on with her life as usual after one of her fellow guild members, the Warlock Zaboo, shows up at her front door. Felicia Day and Joss Whedon both starred in the web series Dr. Horrible's Sing-Along Blog, which Joss Whedon acknowledges was somewhat inspired by The Guild. On October 2, 2012, Geek & Sundry broadcast the first episode of the sixth season. Felicia Day stated that the conclusion of The Guild webseries was discussed in a phone conversation that took place following the conclusion of the sixth season.

The jazz singer Al Jarreau performed the show's theme tune, which became a smash. The show is also recognized with making Willis a star and giving Shepherd with critical acclaim following a succession of unsuccessful efforts. "The Dream Sequence Always Rings Twice" was voted #34 in TV Guide's list of the 100 Greatest Episodes of All Time in 1997. In2007, Time magazine ranked the series among the "100 Best TV Shows of All Time." TV Guide featured David and Maddie on their list of the greatest television couples of all time.

movie_description: From September 29, 1979 until January 15, 1980, CBS aired the American television series Paris. The show, a crime thriller, features James Earl Jones in his first starring role on television and was developed by Steven Bochco, who went on to star in Hill Street Blues and NYPD Blue. Captain Woody Paris of the Los Angeles Police Department supervised a team of young detectives, and the show focused on his experiences as a leader. Officers Charlie Bogart, Ernesto Villas, and Willie Miller were among the rookie investigators under the command of Sergeant Stacy Erickson. Jerome Bench (Hank Garrett), Paris' supervisor and Lee Chamberlin (Lee Chamberlin), Paris's wife, were featured prominently in the storylines in an unusual turn for police dramas of that era. Paris was also shown to be a part-time criminology lecturer at a nearby university. CBS booked Paris in one of the worst conceivable time slots on a weekly schedule: Saturdays at 10 p.m./9 p.m. Central. Only Hart to Hart on ABC made it past its first 13 weeks of production in the 1979-80 season, when it premiered against the competition on all three networks. No matter how many times it was shifted, CBS couldn't save it. Executive producer Bochco's iconic Hill Street Blues would be premiered on NBC during the following season, thanks to Edward DeBlasio's production for MTM Enterprises.
cast: Lee Chamberlin, James Earl Jones, Michael Warren, Cecilia Hart, Hank Garrett

movie_description: At the tail end of the 1950s, when the United States was still relatively naive, the savage and senseless murder of a family in the Midwest outraged the entire country. Dick Hickock, age20, is serving time in state prison when he overhears a cellmate talking about a wealthy rancher who hid $10,000 in cash in a safe at his home. When Dick is finally let out on parole, he recruits fellow parolee Perry Smith, who is also 20 years old, to help him find the hidden stockpile. In the middle of the night in November of1959, Dick and Perry broke into the home that Herb Clutter owned in Holcomb, Kansas. They were furious because there was nowhere safe to hide, so they woke up the sleeping family and ruthlessly murdered them all. Two friends who stopped by the house before going to church on Sunday discovered the bodies. The murders stun the inhabitants of the Great Plains town, where it is common practice to walk about with doors unlocked. The Kansas Bureau of Investigation's Detective Alvin Dewey is in charge of the investigation; however, there are no leads, no clear motive, and no suspects in the crime...

movie_description: Animation series Bob and Margaret, produced in both the United Kingdom and Canada, aired across the globe. This animated series was created by Canadian David Fine and British Alison Snowden for Toronto-based animation studio Nelvana. It was inspired by the Academy Award-winning short film Bob's Birthday, which won the Best Animated Short Film Oscar in1994, and featured the same characters. The show is one of the few Canadian productions to have received regular airtime in the United States. When it aired in prime time on Global Television in Canada, it was the most watched Canadian-produced animated series in the history of the network. Couple Bob and Margaret Fish, a middle-aged couple without children and two dogs named William and Elizabeth, starred in the show. Margaret is a podiatrist, and Bob is a dentist. Everyday concerns and mid-life crises plague Bob and Margaret. Stories frequently center on the banal, but they do it in a way that is both universal and relatable to the audience. Shopping can be difficult, and they have to put up with pals who are a pain in the neck but owe them dinner. First season Bob and Margaret lived in Balham, a South London neighborhood, for the first two seasons of the show. Third and Fourth Seasons were filmed in Toronto, Canada. This allowed the authors to play with the hilarity of cultural differences. The decision was spurred by the fact that many Canadian tax incentives are conditional on stories taking place in Canada, which prompted the change. In order to maintain the series' financial viability, this change was necessary. The show's creators have chosen to take a more executive role in the final two seasons, evaluating and assisting on scripts but not getting as deeply involved as they were in the previous two. Snowden continued to give Margaret's voice, while Andy Hamilton's voice was replaced by Brian George for Bob's character.

movie_description: The Hakkenden is an OVA series that was produced by AIC and is split into two parts, with the second part being titled Shinsh. In1999, a continuation of the Shin Hakkenden television series began airing. The epic novel Nans Satomi Hakkenden, which was written by Kyokutei Bakin during the later half of the Edo Period, serves as the inspiration for the anime. The novel has the title of being the longest novel in the canon of traditional Japanese literature, consisting of a total of 106 volumes. The animation of The Hakkenden is particularly noteworthy due to the fact that it employs an unconventional style for the entirety of the series, shifting between a number of different aesthetic approaches. In addition, the series is well-known for the significant amount of symbolic imagery and concepts that it employs throughout its episodes. This helps the series bridge the gap between animation and art. It is also recognized for bringing a contemporary viewpoint to a literary classic. This is due to the fact that it examines and reexamines archaic and morally ambiguous ideas such as feudal loyalty and devotion throughout the course of many of the conflicts that occur in the story. This is one of the reasons why it has become so well-known. The "THE" that appears at the beginning of the title is not, in point of fact, a translation formality; rather, it is an actual component of the title written in English. It is possible that the authors of the series chose to include it on purpose so as to purposely give a sense of modernity.
cast: N/A

movie_description: Call of the Wildman is an American reality show that airs on the network Animal Planet. The show is currently on its third season. The show follows the adventures of "The Turtleman," a Kentucky woodsman named Ernie Brown, Jr. Brown runs a business to get rid of animals that bother people. With the help of his friend Neal James and his dog Lolly, he catches the animals without hurting them and lets them go back into the wild. Most of the show is filmed near Brown's home in Lebanon, Kentucky. At age 7, Brown started catching snapping turtles in ponds near his home. Animal Planet producers heard about him after an episode of Kentucky Educational Television's Kentucky Afield show that showed him catching turtles with his bare hands went viral on YouTube. After network executives went to see Brown in person and did some initial filming, they decided to make a 12-episode season of the show with the working title The Turtleman of Wild Kentucky. Soon after, the title was changed to Call of the Wildman, which is a reference to Brown's unique yell that is used to mark his actions throughout the series. The series was Animal Planet's most-watched show in the fourth quarter of 2011 and was picked up for a second, 16-episode season that started in June 2012. Animal Planet re-released the series, called Call of the Wildman: More Live Action, in October 2012 with extra features and trivia.

movie_description: Lights Out was a popular old-time radio show in the United States, and it was an early example of a network series devoted to horror and the supernatural, predating Suspense and Inner Sanctum. From January 1934 to the summer of1947, numerous versions of Lights Out appeared on various networks at various times, and the series eventually made the transfer to television. Lights Out was first broadcast on television in 1946 as a series of four specials produced by Fred Coe, who also provided three of the scripts. "First Person Singular," which is narrated exclusively from the point of view of an unseen murderer who kills his irritating wife and ends up being executed, was commissioned by NBC and Cooper wrote the script. movie_description: Miracles is an American drama television series starring Skeet Ulrich and Angus Macfadyen. The series, created by Richard Hatem and Michael Petroni, has been described as a "spiritual equivalent of The X-Files" by its creators. Following the pilot, Angel co-creator David Greenwalt acted as executive producer and lead writer for the remaining twelve episodes. Miracles follows Paul Callan, a Catholic Church investigator of modern miracles who questions his faith after continually discovering conventional explanations for various alleged incidents. After seeing a true, supernatural miracle that saves his life, only to have his findings ignored due to a lack of evidence, Paul leaves the Church and is asked by Alva Keel to join his organization Sodalitas Quaerito, which investigates and catalogs "unexplainable" incidents. Paul and Alva, along with former police officer Evelyn Santos, seek to combat the impending "darkness" before it's too late. On January27,2003, the series debuted as part of ABC's new "Super Monday" lineup. Six episodes were aired on ABC before the series was canceled due to low ratings, with the final episode attracting only 5.7 million viewers on March31, 2003. Several times during its run, the series was interrupted by rebroadcasts of the documentary special Living with Michael Jackson and newsmagazine specials about the then-developing Iraq War. Fans of Miracles, outraged by the cancellation and what they viewed as ABC's mismanagement of the show's Monday 10:00pm timeslot, launched a fan drive to bring the show back. Fans scribbled messages on napkins and mailed them to several networks in the hopes that the show would be revived by another network, but efforts were futile, and the show did not last beyond its initial order of thirteen episodes.
cast: Skeet Ulrich, Marisa Ramirez, Angus Macfadyen, Héctor Elizondo, Sean Galuszka
